html.body: P27KIP module p27KIP1 is a cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor. It binds to CycD1/CDK4,6, CycE1/CDK2 and CycA2/CDK2. However, p27KIP1 seems to have an activating role in the case of CycD1/CDK4,6 association: it favours the binding of the complex and directs its accumulation to the nucleus, as already mentioned in module CycD1/CDK4,6. p27KIP1 has been found to co-immunoprecipitate with the active complex. On the contrary, when bound to CycE1/CDK2 and CycA2/CDK2, p27KIP1 acts as a stoichiometric inhibitor (PMID:10385618). Initially in the nucleus, p27KIP1 is phosphorylated by Akt1, which induces its translocation to the cytoplasm where it can no longer interact with the CDK complexes. Towards the end of S phase, CycE1/CDK2 phosphorylates p27KIP1 to target it for degradation (see module CycE1/CDK2).
